 View CloudWatch Logs with Open-Source Tools
Prerequisites
Basic Linux command line knowledge
Understanding of log files and their purpose
Familiarity with text editors (nano or vim)
SSH access to a Linux machine
Learning Objectives
By the end of this lab, you will be able to:

Set up and configure a local logging system using open-source tools
Create and organize log groups for different applications
Stream application logs to a centralized logging service
Filter and search through log events efficiently
Identify and analyze error entries in logs
Environment Setup
What You'll Need
Al Nafi provides a bare-metal Linux cloud machine. Click the "Start Lab" button to access your environment.

Install Required Tools
We'll use Loki (log aggregation) and Promtail (log shipper) as open-source alternatives to CloudWatch.

Update your system:
sudo apt update
Install required dependencies:
sudo apt install -y wget curl unzip
Download and install Loki:
cd /tmp
wget https://github.com/grafana/loki/releases/download/v2.9.3/loki-linux-amd64.zip
unzip loki-linux-amd64.zip
sudo mv loki-linux-amd64 /usr/local/bin/loki
sudo chmod +x /usr/local/bin/loki
Download and install Promtail:
wget https://github.com/grafana/loki/releases/download/v2.9.3/promtail-linux-amd64.zip
unzip promtail-linux-amd64.zip
sudo mv promtail-linux-amd64 /usr/local/bin/promtail
sudo chmod +x /usr/local/bin/promtail
Install LogCLI (for querying logs):
wget https://github.com/grafana/loki/releases/download/v2.9.3/logcli-linux-amd64.zip
unzip logcli-linux-amd64.zip
sudo mv logcli-linux-amd64 /usr/local/bin/logcli
sudo chmod +x /usr/local/bin/logcli
Task 1: Enable Logging and Create Log Groups
Step 1: Configure Loki
Create a configuration file for Loki:

sudo mkdir -p /etc/loki
sudo nano /etc/loki/config.yml
Add the following configuration:

auth_enabled: false

server:
  http_listen_port: 3100

ingester:
  lifecycler:
    address: 127.0.0.1
    ring:
      kvstore:
        store: inmemory
      replication_factor: 1
  chunk_idle_period: 5m
  chunk_retain_period: 30s

schema_config:
  configs:
    - from: 2020-10-24
      store: boltdb
      object_store: filesystem
      schema: v11
      index:
        prefix: index_
        period: 24h

storage_config:
  boltdb:
    directory: /tmp/loki/index
  filesystem:
    directory: /tmp/loki/chunks

limits_config:
  enforce_metric_name: false
  reject_old_samples: true
  reject_old_samples_max_age: 168h

chunk_store_config:
  max_look_back_period: 0s

table_manager:
  retention_deletes_enabled: false
  retention_period: 0s
Save and exit (Ctrl+X, then Y, then Enter).

Step 2: Start Loki Service
sudo mkdir -p /tmp/loki/index /tmp/loki/chunks
loki -config.file=/etc/loki/config.yml &
Verify Loki is running:

curl http://localhost:3100/ready
You should see "ready" as output.

Step 3: Create a Sample Application with Logs
Create a simple Python application that generates logs:

mkdir -p ~/log-demo
cd ~/log-demo
nano app.py
Add this code:

#!/usr/bin/env python3
import logging
import time
import random

# Configure logging
logging.basicConfig(
    level=logging.INFO,
    format='%(asctime)s - %(name)s - %(levelname)s - %(message)s',
    handlers=[
        logging.FileHandler('/tmp/app.log'),
        logging.StreamHandler()
    ]
)

logger = logging.getLogger('DemoApp')

def main():
    """
    Generate sample log entries including errors
    """
    counter = 0
    while counter < 20:
        counter += 1
        
        # Generate different types of log entries
        if counter % 5 == 0:
            logger.error(f"Error processing request {counter}: Connection timeout")
        elif counter % 3 == 0:
            logger.warning(f"Warning: High memory usage detected at iteration {counter}")
        else:
            logger.info(f"Successfully processed request {counter}")
        
        time.sleep(2)

if __name__ == "__main__":
    logger.info("Application started")
    main()
    logger.info("Application finished")
Save and exit.

Make it executable and run it:

chmod +x app.py
python3 app.py &
Task 2: Stream Logs and Filter Events
Step 1: Configure Promtail to Stream Logs
Create Promtail configuration:

sudo mkdir -p /etc/promtail
sudo nano /etc/promtail/config.yml
Add this configuration:

server:
  http_listen_port: 9080
  grpc_listen_port: 0

positions:
  filename: /tmp/positions.yaml

clients:
  - url: http://localhost:3100/loki/api/v1/push

scrape_configs:
  - job_name: system
    static_configs:
      - targets:
          - localhost
        labels:
          job: varlogs
          __path__: /var/log/*.log

  - job_name: application
    static_configs:
      - targets:
          - localhost
        labels:
          job: app
          app: demo
          __path__: /tmp/app.log
Save and exit.

Step 2: Start Promtail
promtail -config.file=/etc/promtail/config.yml &
Wait 10 seconds for logs to be collected and sent to Loki.

Step 3: Query All Logs
Set up LogCLI environment:

export LOKI_ADDR=http://localhost:3100
View all application logs:

logcli query '{job="app"}' --limit=50 --since=5m
Step 4: Filter for Error Entries
Query only ERROR level logs:

logcli query '{job="app"} |= "ERROR"' --limit=20 --since=5m
Step 5: Filter for Specific Patterns
Find logs with "Connection timeout":

logcli query '{job="app"} |= "Connection timeout"' --limit=10 --since=5m
Find WARNING logs:

logcli query '{job="app"} |= "WARNING"' --limit=10 --since=5m
Step 6: Use Advanced Filtering
Filter logs by multiple criteria:

logcli query '{job="app"} |= "request" | json | line_format "{{.msg}}"' --since=5m
Count error occurrences:

logcli query 'count_over_time({job="app"} |= "ERROR" [5m])' --since=5m
Verification
Verify Log Collection
Check Loki is receiving logs:
curl -G -s "http://localhost:3100/loki/api/v1/label" | python3 -m json.tool
Expected output should show labels like "job", "app", etc.

Verify log count:
logcli stats '{job="app"}' --since=5m
You should see statistics showing ingested logs.

Check for errors in your logs:
logcli query '{job="app"} |= "ERROR"' --limit=5 --since=5m
You should see at least 4 error entries (every 5th iteration from 20 total).

Verify log file exists:
ls -lh /tmp/app.log
cat /tmp/app.log | grep ERROR
